First vegetation survey from Woods Lake

Leon Barmuta & Inger Visby

23 December 2015

Here is the vegetation survey data from June 2016 in Woods Lake.

This is a quick, rough and ready compilation of an .html file, so there will be a few warning messages and other crap appearing in the output.

## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
## Joining by: "surveyPoint"

Here are the names and locations of the survey points with vegetation recorded at them. Note that F09 is the only point that seems to have been missed.

In the following, pink dots denote survey points which get obscured by black dots which are sized according to the (maximum) cover value (%) recorded for that survey point.

There were only 5 locations with maximum cover < 5%; all were on the edge of the lake at the surveyed time. These are marked in dark olive green in the map below.

The final map plot is for each species. Size of dot represents percentage cover.

Here is a numerical summary of the vegetation data. Cover of each taxon is recorded as a percentage of projected area of each taxon in the video footage (i.e.in some situations the cover values of all species at a survey point will sum to > 100%). Depth is recorded to within approximately 0.25 m of the sediment surface (the tops of the plants get in the way), so add 0.25 m to those values. There are two missing values for depth, which we could interpolate linearly from adjacent stations.

And now for the bivariate plots for the three dominant taxa Loess smoothers superposed to visualise any trends; dots with alpha transparency set so darker dots denote several values superposed at the same plot location.

Charophyte cover, when its there, tends to be negatively correlated with cover by Elodea canadensis.

Just for fun, it may interesting to examing percent cover for each taxon versus depth.

So Charophytes have less cover at depths > 2.75 m, Elodea canadensis really doesnt show much of a change with depth, whereas Potamogeton orchreatus seems to show greater cover values in deeper water. I note in passing that upper quantile relationships may be more informative than simple measures of central tendency and quantile regression is something we can look at later.
